        [
          "Staff Generated History"
        ],
        [
          "These days your genius would be \"savant\". You'd be \"inovative\", \"progressive\", and \"savvy\". But during the 20's, so was everyone else. The techboom's intensity tossed you into a large pool of other inovative types. With the 20's though, also came tuberculosis. You saw and knew the cure, it was available to buy in your trunk for 30 cents! You sold dozens of bottles of the stuff for ailing familes. You'd never felt so accomplished, giving back to your community. However this only lasted so long, when the users of your home remedy only died in drug induced comas, high on morphine. You lost your credibility, and buying customers now slammed doors in your face and stuck harsh whispers into your back. Your reputation lost wasn't the worth though, it was when your own daughter began to cough blood. Your miracle medicine failed. She coughed so much, and it got everywhere. You couldn't stop the blood from coming out of your daughter, no matter how hard you poured it back down her throat. The night she died you walked down to theocean, drunk on your own damned syrup. You died in a harbor, sinking to the bottom. The last face you saw in your own watery grave was your daughter, her perfect curls closing in on you, her small white teeth so sharp on your wrist. When you woke the night next, your daughter sat in your lap waiting to walk you through your new life, you quickly adjusted and took it fairly well when you learned your own daughter was at least 200 years your senior. You began to wonder when it was that she found her way into your life, dominating you to believe you had always had her. She critiqued your sales pitches, and directed you into a different art - the art of counterfeit and manipulation. You learned how to spot and call out fake art, fake products, anything. And with that knowledge you learned how to make your own, selling Sabbat artifacts off to the highest bidders and raving Cainites."
        ],
